        "patch":  "@@ -0,0 +1,328 @@\n+# Execution Report\n+\n+DISPATCH_ID: ISSUE-110\n+AUTHOR: Executor / Claude\n+TIMESTAMP: 2026-05-23_10-32-36+0300\n+RELATED_FILES:\n+- tools/architecture-lints/src/kernel_isolation.rs â€” read-only audit (no edits)\n+- tools/architecture-lints/tests/kernel_isolation_test.rs â€” read-only audit (no edits)\n+- Cargo.toml â€” read-only audit (no edits)\n+- crates/io-gltf/Cargo.toml â€” read-only audit (no edits)\n+- crates/io-gltf/src/lib.rs â€” read-only audit (no edits)\n+- crates/io-gltf/src/image.rs â€” read-only audit (no edits)\n+- crates/io-gltf/src/import.rs â€” read-only audit (no edits)\n+- crates/io-gltf/src/export.rs â€” read-only audit (no edits)\n+- crates/io-image/Cargo.toml â€” read-only audit (no edits)\n+- crates/io-image/src/lib.rs â€” read-only audit (no edits)\n+- crates/io-image/src/format_detect.rs â€” read-only audit (no edits)\n+- crates/io-step/Cargo.toml â€” read-only audit (no edits)\n+- crates/io-step/src/lib.rs â€” read-only audit (no edits)\n+- crates/io-stl/Cargo.toml â€” read-only audit (no edits)\n+- crates/io-stl/src/lib.rs â€” read-only audit (no edits)\n+STATUS: AWAITING_REVIEW\n+\n+## Task Packet Reference\n+\n+`ai_handoffs/ISSUE-110_TASK_2026-05-23_10-25-49+0300.md`\n+\n+## Pre-Execution Review Consumed\n+\n+No pre-execution review issued for this dispatch.\n+\n+## What I Changed\n+\n+### Source\n+\n+- None. This dispatch is a read-only preflight audit; no source, test,\n+  manifest, lockfile, lint, workflow, script, doc, schema, or existing\n+  packet was modified.\n+\n+### Tests\n+\n+- None added or modified.\n+\n+### Docs\n+\n+- None added or modified. The only new files written by this dispatch are\n+  this `ISSUE-110_EXEC_*.md` packet (and its optional `.meta.json` sidecar\n+  produced if `new-handoff.ps1 -Finalize` is later invoked by the\n+  orchestrator). Both are protocol artifacts explicitly permitted by the\n+  Task Packet\u0027s `MAY add new files` clause.\n+\n+## Per-File Summary\n+\n+Skip â€” bullet lists above are sufficient.\n+\n+## IO Formats Metadata Preflight Answers\n+\n+### 1. What metadata shape does the lint read?\n+\n+The `kernel-isolation` lint at `tools/architecture-lints/src/kernel_isolation.rs`\n+reads each workspace package\u0027s Cargo metadata via `cargo metadata`, identifies\n+the `io-*` packages, and then extracts the `package.metadata.rge.formats` array\n+from each. Specifically, `extract_formats` walks\n+`pkg.metadata.get(\"rge\").and_then(|rge| rge.get(\"formats\")).and_then(|f| f.as_array())`\n+and lower-cases every string entry. Concretely (see lines 19-35 and 73-87):\n+\n+```toml\n+# crates/io-\u003cname\u003e/Cargo.toml\n+[package.metadata.rge]\n+formats = [\"gltf\", \"glb\"]\n+```\n+\n+Rules verified from the source and from the integration tests in\n+`tools/architecture-lints/tests/kernel_isolation_test.rs`:\n+\n+- Each string is an extension name, lower-case, **no leading dot**\n+  (see crate doc-comment lines 27-28 and `extract_formats` calls\n+  `str::to_lowercase` on every entry).\n+- A format claimed by â‰¥ 2 detected `io-*` crates is a violation (exit 1)\n+  (lines 128-157; integration tests 4, 5, 6, 8 cover this).\n+- Missing `[package.metadata.rge]` on an `io-*` crate is **only a stderr\n+  warning**, never a violation (Option B, lines 30-35 of the source and\n+  the `test_missing_metadata_is_warning_not_violation` test, lines\n+  301-334 of the test file). The lint still exits 0.\n+- No alias normalization is performed inside the lint: `jpg` and `jpeg`\n+  are treated as distinct extension strings; the lint only compares\n+  lower-cased literals. Avoiding overlap-by-aliasing therefore requires\n+  manifest discipline, not lint logic â€” see resolution in Â§4.\n+\n+### 2. Which workspace IO crates are detected?\n+\n+`is_io_crate` (lines 54-71) detects an `io-*` crate by either:\n+\n+1. Package name starts with `rge-io-` (canonical workspace prefix) or\n+   bare `io-` (synthetic fixture convention used by tests).\n+2. Manifest path lives at `crates/io-*/Cargo.toml` (fallback that\n+   identifies crates whose package names don\u0027t start with `io-`/`rge-io-`).\n+\n+From the root `Cargo.toml` (`A:\\RCAD\\RGE\\Cargo.toml`, lines 96-103, the\n+\"Tier 2 â€” Importers / exporters\" block), the workspace IO members are:\n+\n+- `crates/io-gltf` â€” package name `rge-io-gltf` (manifest line 2)\n+- `crates/io-step` â€” package name `rge-io-step` (manifest line 2)\n+- `crates/io-stl` â€” package name `rge-io-stl` (manifest line 2)\n+- `crates/io-obj` â€” detected (path-based + likely `rge-io-obj` name)\n+- `crates/io-image` â€” package name `rge-io-image` (manifest line 2)\n+- `crates/io-audio` â€” detected (path-based + likely `rge-io-audio` name)\n+- `crates/io-3mf` â€” detected (path-based + likely `rge-io-3mf` name)\n+\n+Per the Task Packet\u0027s Constraints / Non-Goals, only the four target\n+crates (`rge-io-gltf`, `rge-io-image`, `rge-io-step`, `rge-io-stl`)\n+receive exact format arrays in this preflight; `io-obj`, `io-audio`, and\n+`io-3mf` are listed as detected members only, with no ownership decision\n+made here.\n+\n+### 3. What exact four-crate format arrays are implied?\n+\n+Based exclusively on the inspected source, manifests, and crate-level\n+doc-comments:\n+\n+- `rge-io-gltf`: `[\"gltf\", \"glb\"]`\n+- `rge-io-image`: `[\"png\", \"jpg\", \"jpeg\", \"exr\", \"hdr\"]`\n+- `rge-io-step`: `[\"step\", \"stp\", \"iges\", \"igs\"]`\n+- `rge-io-stl`: `[\"stl\"]`\n+\n+Evidence per crate:\n+\n+- **`rge-io-gltf`** â€” `crates/io-gltf/Cargo.toml:3` description \"glTF 2.0\n+  import/export\"; `crates/io-gltf/src/lib.rs:20-26` and the doc-comment\n+  for `import_glb` / `export_glb` confirm `.glb` (binary glTF) is the\n+  primary on-disk surface. `crates/io-gltf/src/import.rs:1-46` (top-level\n+  doc + `import_glb`/`import_glb_bytes`) and `src/export.rs:1-53` (GLB\n+  layout doc + `CHUNK_TYPE_*` / `GLB_MAGIC` constants) operate on the\n+  GLB container. The `.gltf` JSON-only sibling extension is the same\n+  format family (glTF 2.0 Â§4.4 / Â§4.5); both extensions belong to this\n+  crate per the canonical glTF specification, so the array pairs them.\n+- **`rge-io-image`** â€” `crates/io-image/Cargo.toml:3` description\n+  \"PNG/JPEG/EXR/HDR via image + exr\"; `crates/io-image/src/lib.rs:14-15`\n+  states \"this crate is the **only** path for PNG / JPEG / EXR / HDR\n+  raster ingestion in RGE\"; `crates/io-image/src/format_detect.rs:11-44`\n+  defines `ImageFormat::{Png, Jpeg, OpenExr, RadianceHdr}` as the only\n+  recognized variants. JPEG carries both `jpg` and `jpeg` extensions in\n+  real-world usage and the lint string-matches without alias collapse,\n+  so both must be listed (see Â§4).\n+- **`rge-io-step`** â€” `crates/io-step/Cargo.toml:3` description\n+  \"STEP/IGES import via OCCT\"; `crates/io-step/src/lib.rs` is a stub\n+  noting \"Architecture frozen at v0.8; implementation pending\". STEP\n+  files carry `.step` and `.stp`; IGES files carry `.iges` and `.igs`;\n+  the lint requires each spelling listed individually (see Â§4).\n+- **`rge-io-stl`** â€” `crates/io-stl/Cargo.toml:3` description\n+  \"STL import/export\"; `crates/io-stl/src/lib.rs` is a stub. STL has\n+  exactly one canonical extension `.stl`.\n+\n+### 4. Which ownership ambiguities and aliases are resolved, and which remain?\n+\n+Resolved (the implied four arrays above already encode these):\n+\n+- **`jpg` and `jpeg`** â€” both belong to `rge-io-image`. The lint\n+  string-compares lower-cased literals and performs no alias collapse\n+  (`format_detect.rs` and `extract_formats` carry no normalization),\n+  so both spellings must be claimed by io-image. Cargo description and\n+  feature flag `image = { ..., features = [\"png\", \"jpeg\", \"hdr\"] }`\n+  (manifest line 13) confirm JPEG is owned here.\n+- **`step` and `stp`** â€” both belong to `rge-io-step`. Cargo description\n+  \"STEP/IGES import via OCCT\" covers both spellings of the STEP family.\n+- **`iges` and `igs`** â€” both belong to `rge-io-step`. Same Cargo\n+  description covers both spellings of the IGES family. The combined\n+  array `[\"step\", \"stp\", \"iges\", \"igs\"]` therefore consolidates STEP\n+  and IGES ownership under one crate, matching the manifest\u0027s stated\n+  scope.\n+- **`gltf` and `glb`** â€” both belong to `rge-io-gltf`. The `gltf`\n+  workspace dependency is gated to `default-features = false` with\n+  only `[\"utils\", \"names\"]` features (manifest lines 16-18) precisely\n+  to keep this crate the sole owner of the glTF container (per the\n+  one-importer-per-format rule, PLAN Â§1.6.4/Â§1.6.5 referenced in the\n+  crate\u0027s own `lib.rs` and `Cargo.toml` comments).\n+- **Embedded raster bytes inside glTF / GLB** â€” codec-owned by\n+  `rge-io-image`. `crates/io-gltf/src/image.rs:1-44` is explicit:\n+  io-gltf extracts buffer-view bytes and `data:image/...;base64,...`\n+  URIs from the glTF document, then **delegates decoding** to\n+  `rge_io_image::load_bytes`. The crate-level doc on `image.rs` and\n+  the dependency-rationale comment in `crates/io-gltf/Cargo.toml`\n+  lines 12-29 spell this out: \"io-image stays the single owner of\n+  raster codecs; io-gltf only handles the glTF embedding semantics.\"\n+  Therefore raster extension strings (`png`, `jpg`, `jpeg`, etc.) must\n+  NOT appear in `rge-io-gltf`\u0027s formats array â€” they belong to io-image\n+  and adding them to io-gltf would trigger the overlap violation.\n+\n+Remaining (intentionally not resolved here):\n+\n+- Ownership of formats for `io-obj`, `io-audio`, and `io-3mf` is out of\n+  scope per the Task Packet\u0027s Constraints / Non-Goals. The Task Packet\n+  explicitly forbids deciding their arrays in this dispatch; they are\n+  listed in Â§2 as detected workspace IO members only.\n+\n+### 5. What is the smallest safe follow-up?\n+\n+A separate, later, **manifest-only** dispatch that adds exactly one\n+`[package.metadata.rge]` block per target crate to the four target\n+`Cargo.toml` files, with NO source, test, lint, workflow, script,\n+docs, lockfile, or behavior changes bundled in:\n+\n+```toml\n+# crates/io-gltf/Cargo.toml\n+[package.metadata.rge]\n+formats = [\"gltf\", \"glb\"]\n+\n+# crates/io-image/Cargo.toml\n+[package.metadata.rge]\n+formats = [\"png\", \"jpg\", \"jpeg\", \"exr\", \"hdr\"]\n+\n+# crates/io-step/Cargo.toml\n+[package.metadata.rge]\n+formats = [\"step\", \"stp\", \"iges\", \"igs\"]\n+\n+# crates/io-stl/Cargo.toml\n+[package.metadata.rge]\n+formats = [\"stl\"]\n+```\n+\n+That follow-up MUST NOT touch `tools/architecture-lints/**`,\n+`crates/io-*/src/**`, `crates/io-*/tests/**`, `Cargo.lock`, any workflow,\n+or any doc. It also MUST NOT introduce alias normalization into the\n+lint â€” alias coverage stays a manifest concern, as the lint reads\n+literals without normalization (see Â§1 and Â§4). Detected-but-out-of-scope\n+crates (`io-obj`, `io-audio`, `io-3mf`) will continue to emit only\n+stderr warnings under Option B until separate dispatches decide their\n+arrays.\n+\n+## Verification Results\n+\n+- Read-only inspection of all required paths:\n+  - `tools/architecture-lints/src/kernel_isolation.rs` â€” read in full\n+    (161 lines). PASS.\n+  - `tools/architecture-lints/tests/kernel_isolation_test.rs` â€” read in\n+    full (393 lines). PASS.\n+  - root `Cargo.toml` â€” read in full (284 lines), workspace IO member\n+    block at lines 96-103 confirmed. PASS.\n+  - `crates/io-gltf/**` â€” `Cargo.toml`, `src/lib.rs`, `src/image.rs`,\n+    `src/import.rs` (head), `src/export.rs` (head) read; full file\n+    listing enumerated via Glob. PASS.\n+  - `crates/io-image/**` â€” `Cargo.toml`, `src/lib.rs`,\n+    `src/format_detect.rs` read; full file listing enumerated via Glob.\n+    PASS.\n+  - `crates/io-step/**` â€” `Cargo.toml`, `src/lib.rs` (stub) read; full\n+    file listing enumerated via Glob. PASS.\n+  - `crates/io-stl/**` â€” `Cargo.toml`, `src/lib.rs` (stub) read; full\n+    file listing enumerated via Glob. PASS.\n+- `git status --short --untracked-files=all` BEFORE writing this packet:\n+  ```\n+  ?? ai_handoffs/ISSUE-110_TASK_2026-05-23_10-25-49+0300.md\n+  ?? ai_handoffs/ISSUE-110_TASK_2026-05-23_10-25-49+0300.meta.json\n+  ```\n+  Only the planner-attributed TASK packet and its sidecar â€” no\n+  executor-attributed source/manifest/lockfile/lint/workflow/script/test/\n+  doc/`.ai` changes. PASS.\n+- `git diff -- Cargo.toml Cargo.lock tools/architecture-lints crates/io-gltf crates/io-image crates/io-step crates/io-stl .github .ai`:\n+  no output. PASS.\n+- `git status --short --untracked-files=all` AFTER writing this packet:\n+  expected to additionally show only\n+  `?? ai_handoffs/ISSUE-110_EXEC_2026-05-23_10-32-36+0300.md`\n+  (and optionally its `.meta.json` sidecar if `-Finalize` runs). These\n+  are the protocol artifacts explicitly permitted by the Task Packet.\n+- `new-handoff.ps1 -Finalize -PacketPath ai_handoffs/ISSUE-110_EXEC_2026-05-23_10-32-36+0300.md -DryRun`:\n+  ran. Output: \"DRY RUN (finalize) - would derive this sidecar from\n+  the completed packet:\" followed by the derived sidecar JSON\n+  (`schema_version: handoff-sidecar-v1`, `dispatch_id: ISSUE-110`,\n+  `packet_type: EXEC`, `author: Executor / Claude`,\n+  `timestamp: 2026-05-23_10-32-36+0300`, `status: AWAITING_REVIEW`,\n+  `handoff_status: COMPLETE`, `next_role: REVIEWER_AI`, `exit_code: 0`,\n+  and the 15-entry `related_files` array intact). The PowerShell\n+  invocation completed with `$?` True and no error stream output,\n+  i.e. the protocol-finalize gate passed. (This is the packet-protocol\n+  gate explicitly enumerated in the Task Packet\u0027s `Verification Gates`;\n+  it is not one of the forbidden code-verification scripts â€” cargo,\n+  formatters, architecture lints, and `.ai/dispatch.verify.ps1` were\n+  NOT run.)\n+- No `cargo` commands, no tests, no formatters, no `.ai/dispatch.verify.ps1`\n+  run.\n+\n+## Deviations from Task Packet\n+\n+None â€” execution stayed strictly within the Task Packet scope. No source,\n+test, manifest, lockfile, lint, workflow, script, doc, schema, or\n+existing packet was modified. The only new file authored is this EXEC\n+report (and its optional `.meta.json` sidecar at finalize time), both\n+explicitly permitted.\n+\n+## Open Questions for Reviewer\n+\n+- Confirm the `gltf` entry pairing with `glb` in `rge-io-gltf`\u0027s array\n+  is intended even though the on-disk importer/exporter today operates\n+  on `.glb` (binary glTF) only. The crate\u0027s name and the glTF 2.0 spec\n+  cover both extensions as the same format family, and the lint\n+  treats them as separate literals â€” listing both prevents a future\n+  `.gltf` importer from being added in a different crate. Planner\u0027s\n+  expected array in the Task Packet matches this pairing, so this is\n+  flagged as confirmation rather than a deviation.\n+- Confirm that `io-step` and `io-stl` carrying formats arrays on stub\n+  crates is acceptable. The lint already detects them as `io-*` and\n+  currently warns on missing metadata; adding the arrays in the\n+  follow-up will silence the warning and pre-claim ownership even\n+  though no decode/encode implementation exists yet. This matches the\n+  Task Packet\u0027s `Deliverables` exactly.\n+\n+## Worktree State\n+\n+- Tracked files: clean.\n+- Untracked items:\n+  - `ai_handoffs/ISSUE-110_TASK_2026-05-23_10-25-49+0300.md` (planner\n+    artifact, pre-existing).\n+  - `ai_handoffs/ISSUE-110_TASK_2026-05-23_10-25-49+0300.meta.json`\n+    (planner sidecar, pre-existing).\n+  - `ai_handoffs/ISSUE-110_EXEC_2026-05-23_10-32-36+0300.md` (this\n+    EXEC report â€” the single new artifact this dispatch was permitted\n+    to add).\n+- Branch: `ai-dispatch/ISSUE-110`\n+- Last commit: `58ca382` chore(dispatch): queue task #13 io-format metadata preflight\n+\n+---\n+\n+HANDOFF_STATUS: COMPLETE\n+DISPATCH_ID: ISSUE-110\n+AUTHOR: Executor / Claude\n+NEXT_ROLE: REVIEWER_AI\n+EXIT_CODE: 0\n+\n+